# Amendment History: github-auto-merge-no-ci-runs

## v1.4.0 (2026-05-29)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PRs #677/#679/#681/#683 — pr-policy auto-merge race + cascading cancellations (self-heal via auto_merge_enabled event trigger)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Bumped `version` to 1.4.0 (MINOR — new failure mode) and refreshed `date` to 2026-05-29
- Extended `description` frontmatter `Use when:` list with triggers (12)-(14): a PR shows
  failed/cancelled checks but is actually fine because the pr-policy auto-merge check failed
  on the FIRST run and cancelled all sibling jobs via the concurrency group; auto-merge not
  firing right after open but pr-policy failing self-heals once `--auto --squash` propagates
  and the `auto_merge_enabled` trigger re-runs the workflow; cancelled CI jobs after opening
  a PR are diagnosed by comparing `statusCheckRollup` entries' `startedAt` (earlier pr-policy
  run = race, later re-run = authoritative)
- Added an Overview table row for the 2026-05-29 four-PR self-heal observation
- Added three "When to Use" bullets covering the cancelled-sibling cascade, the
  `gh pr checks` flattening trap, and the `auto_merge_enabled` self-heal
- Added a Quick Reference diagnosis block (state==MERGED short-circuit, startedAt filter,
  and the until-loop that exits on MERGED OR a re-run FAILURE)
- Added fix 0 to the Required-Check Gate Race section: trigger the gate workflow on
  `auto_merge_enabled` so it self-heals with no human action (shipped as #681/#683); demoted
  the manual `gh run rerun` to "only if the workflow lacks the auto_merge_enabled trigger"
- Added a "Cascading Cancellations" subsection explaining how one pr-policy failure plus a
  `concurrency: cancel-in-progress` group marks every sibling job `cancelled`, why it
  self-heals, and the 4-step correct-diagnosis procedure
- Added four "Failed Attempts" rows: misreading cancelled siblings via `gh pr checks`,
  counting `cancelled` rollup entries as real failures, considering `--admin`/force-merge,
  and waiting for a manual rerun when the `auto_merge_enabled` trigger already re-fires
- Added a decision-tree branch for "pr-policy FAILURE + many CANCELLED siblings on a
  just-opened PR"
- Added a Verified On row: ProjectHephaestus 2026-05-29 (4 PRs self-healed with zero human
  action via the #681/#683 event trigger)

### Why

ProjectHephaestus's required `pr-policy` gate (part of a `Required Checks` reusable workflow)
runs inside a workflow that uses a `concurrency` group with `cancel-in-progress: true`. When
a PR is first opened, `pr-policy`'s "Check 2: auto-merge enabled" step can run BEFORE
`gh pr merge --auto --squash` has registered auto-merge, so it exits 1. Because of the
concurrency group, that single failure tears down the whole run and marks EVERY sibling job
(lint, tests, security scans, markdownlint, shellcheck, pixi-check, symlink-check,
justfile-check, etc.) as `cancelled`. A freshly-opened PR therefore looks like it broke a
dozen things, when there is exactly one real failure and a cascade of `cancelled` (not
`failed`) siblings. Reading `gh pr checks <N>` flattens those cancelled+superseded entries
together with a later green re-run, which is what made the PRs look broken.

The fix (shipped as ProjectHephaestus #681 / #683, "fix auto-merge race at the root via
event triggers") adds the `auto_merge_enabled` activity type to the gate workflow's
`pull_request` trigger. Once `gh pr merge --auto --squash` takes effect, GitHub re-fires the
whole workflow, `pr-policy` re-evaluates against the now-armed state and passes, the siblings
re-run green, and the PR merges — with NO human action and NO manual `gh run rerun`. Observed
end-to-end across 4 PRs (#677, #679, #681, #683) that all merged green on 2026-05-29. The
correct diagnosis is to check `state` (often already `MERGED`) and filter the rollup by
`startedAt` (the later pr-policy run is authoritative); a genuinely-broken PR is one where
the LATER re-run fails, not the first-run cancellations. Never `--admin`/force-merge to
escape the transient red — waiting ~30-60s lets the event-trigger re-run go green on its own.

