## v1.3.0 (2026-05-21)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PRs #423/#428/#430 — pr-policy auto-merge race
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Bumped `version` to 1.3.0 and refreshed `date` to 2026-05-21
- Extended `description` frontmatter `Use when:` list with trigger (11): a required-check
  gate job (e.g. `pr-policy`) fails with "Auto-merge is not enabled" immediately after PR
  creation though auto-merge IS enabled — a propagation race; re-run the failed job
- Added a "When to Use" bullet covering the pr-policy auto-merge propagation race
- Added a "Required-Check Gate Race (pr-policy)" subsection under Verified Workflow
  describing the race, the `gh run rerun <id> --failed` fix, the "wait for run
  status=completed before rerun" caveat, and the "body edit does not re-trigger
  pull_request" caveat
- Added three new "Failed Attempts" rows: sequential `gh pr create` then `gh pr merge`
  losing the race, editing the PR body expecting CI re-evaluation, and `gh run rerun`
  while the parent run is still in progress

### Why

ProjectHephaestus has a required CI gate job `pr-policy` (part of a `Required Checks`
reusable workflow) that fetches PR metadata LIVE at job runtime via
`gh pr view --json body,autoMergeRequest` plus a GraphQL signature query. The job runs
on the `pull_request` event and fires within ~4 seconds of PR creation. When `gh pr create`
and `gh pr merge --auto --squash` are issued as two sequential commands, `pr-policy` can
read `autoMergeRequest` before the auto-merge enablement has propagated, failing with
`::error::Auto-merge is not enabled on this PR` even though auto-merge is enabled moments
later. This happened on PRs #423 and #428; PR #430 passed first try by enabling auto-merge
fast enough to beat the job scheduling. Because `pr-policy` re-fetches PR metadata live,
re-running the failed job (`gh run rerun <id> --failed`) re-evaluates against the now-correct
state and passes — but the parent run must be `completed` first, and editing the PR body to
add `Closes #N` does not re-trigger the `pull_request` workflow (it fires on
opened/synchronize/reopened, not `edited`), so a re-run is still required after a body edit.

